        pdfPractices: [
          'Think of someone who is passively drifting from God — not rebelling but simply lost in the noise of life. Pray for them this week.',
          'Read Psalm 139:1–12 alongside this parable — God searches even in darkness.',
          'What does it mean for you personally that God lit a lamp and swept the house looking for you?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'The parable introduces a female protagonist in a parallel to the male shepherd, showing that both men and women reflect God\'s searching love. For a Jewish audience, attributing God\'s character to a woman was itself striking and inclusive.',
        historicalContext: 'A drachma was equivalent to a Roman denarius — one day\'s pay. Houses in first-century Palestine were dark with small windows; a lamp and broom were practical necessities for finding something lost on an earthen floor.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'The parable is notable for its female image of God — unusual in first-century Judaism but consistent with Jesus\' practice of inclusive imagery. Green and others note that Luke pairs male and female parables throughout his Gospel (e.g., mustard seed/leaven, shepherd/woman) to underline the universality of grace.',
        exegeticalNotes: 'The verb \u1f10\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u1ff6\u03c2 \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6 (epimel\u014ds z\u0113tei, "seeks diligently") uses an adverb that appears only here in the NT — it emphasises the care and attention of the search. The coin is passive (it does not return on its own), unlike the sheep or the son — the recovery is entirely due to the seeker.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Unmerciful Servant',
        reference: 'Matthew 18:23\u201335',
        theme: 'Forgiving Others',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Grace & Forgiveness/The Unmerciful Servant.webp',
        icon: Icons.balance_rounded,
        summary: 'Forgiven an unpayable debt, a servant refuses to forgive a small one. What has God forgiven you?',
        verse: 'Therefore the Kingdom of Heaven is like a certain king, who wanted to reconcile accounts with his servants. When he had begun to reconcile, one was brought to him who owed him ten thousand talents. But because he couldn\'t pay, his lord commanded him to be sold, with his wife, his children, and all that he had, and payment to be made. The servant therefore fell down and kneeled before him, saying, "Lord, have patience with me, and I will repay you all!" The lord of that servant, being moved with compassion, released him, and forgave him the debt. But that servant went out, and found one of his fellow servants, who owed him one hundred denarii, and he grabbed him, and took him by the throat, saying, "Pay me what you owe!"',
        statementInBrief: 'A servant forgiven an astronomically unpayable debt immediately refuses to forgive a tiny debt owed to him. His fellow servants report him; the king reverses his forgiveness. The parable defines the only possible response to divine grace: extend to others what God has extended to you.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Those who have received mercy must become merciful — there is no other option',
        centralPoint: 'Ten thousand talents was more than the entire GDP of first-century Palestine — a deliberately absurd, unpayable sum. One hundred denarii was roughly four months\' wages. The contrast is the entire point: anyone who understands what God has forgiven them cannot refuse a comparatively tiny debt to another.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Who do you hold a debt against — and do you know how much God has forgiven you?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Write down the name of someone you need to forgive. Bring it to God and ask for the grace to release the debt.',
          'Meditate on Ephesians 4:32 alongside this parable: "forgiving each other, as God in Christ forgave you."',
          'Ask: am I forgiving from a position of one who has been forgiven, or from a position of moral superiority?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable answers Peter\'s question about how many times to forgive a brother — "seven times?" Jesus says seventy-seven (or seventy times seven) — a number so large it ends the counting. The parable explains why: the forgiven have no grounds for withholding forgiveness.',
        historicalContext: 'A talent was worth approximately fifteen to twenty years of a labourer\'s wages; ten thousand talents was a grotesquely impossible sum. One hundred denarii was a real but manageable debt. The debtor\'s throat-grabbing (\u1f10\u03c0\u03bd\u03af\u03b3\u03b5\u03bd, epnigen) is viscerally violent — there is no mercy in his treatment of his fellow servant.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France and Hagner both note that the parable is not teaching that forgiveness can be revoked by God — rather, it uses hyperbole to show that failing to forgive reveals one never truly received God\'s forgiveness in the heart. The theological point is about the transformative nature of grace.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03bc\u03c5\u03c1\u03af\u03c9\u03bd \u03c4\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd (myri\u014dn talant\u014dn, "ten thousand talents") — \u03bc\u03c5\u03c1\u03b9\u03ac\u03c2 was the largest Greek numeral; "ten thousand talents" was the largest conceivable sum in ancient thought. The contrast with \u1f11\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u1f78\u03bd \u03b4\u03b7\u03bd\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u03c9\u03bd (one hundred denarii) is mathematically approximately 600,000:1.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Pharisee and the Tax Collector',
        reference: 'Luke 18:9\u201314',
        theme: 'Humility',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Grace & Forgiveness/The Pharaisee and the Tax Collector.webp',
        icon: Icons.volunteer_activism_rounded,
        summary: 'Two men pray. One leaves justified. God opposes the proud but gives grace to the humble.',
        verse: 'The Pharisee stood and prayed to himself like this: "God, I thank you, that I am not like the rest of men, extortioners, unrighteous, adulterers, or even like this tax collector. I fast twice a week. I give tithes of all that I get." But the tax collector, standing far away, wouldn\'t even lift up his eyes to heaven, but beat his breast, saying, "God, be merciful to me, a sinner!" I tell you, this man went down to his house justified rather than the other; for everyone who exalts himself will be humbled, but everyone who humbles himself will be exalted.',
        statementInBrief: 'Two men pray in the temple. The Pharisee itemises his righteousness; the tax collector beats his chest and asks for mercy. Jesus declares the latter — not the former — to be justified. Self-justification closes the door to God\'s grace; self-emptying opens it.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Justification comes by mercy received, not by righteousness displayed',
        centralPoint: 'The Pharisee\'s prayer is entirely self-referential — it begins and ends with him. The tax collector\'s prayer has nothing to offer except the appeal to mercy. The reversal is the whole point: proximity to God is determined by posture before God, not by achievement before men.',
        pdfQuestion: 'When you come before God, do you come primarily with your performance record or with your need for mercy?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Use the tax collector\'s prayer — "God, be merciful to me, a sinner" — as your daily morning prayer this week.',
          'Examine your prayer life: do your prayers tend to report your faithfulness to God, or to receive from His?',
          'Read Isaiah 66:2 alongside this parable: God looks to the one who trembles at His word.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Luke specifies the audience: "those who trusted in themselves that they were righteous, and looked down on all others" (18:9). The parable is direct confrontation — the Pharisees would have been shocked to hear a tax collector (a Roman collaborator and public sinner) pronounced righteous over one of themselves.',
        historicalContext: 'The Pharisee\'s practices — tithing all and fasting twice weekly — exceeded what the Law required, representing exemplary piety by Jewish standards. Tax collectors were despised as traitors and extortioners. The temple court setting is significant: this was the public space of formal prayer and display.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green (NICNT) reads the parable as Jesus\'s subversion of the honour-shame calculus of his world: the one who accepts shame before God receives honour from God. The word \u03b4\u03b5\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 (dedikaiomenos, "justified") is a forensic term — the tax collector leaves the temple in a state of righteousness he did not possess when he entered.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f31\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03af \u03bc\u03bf\u03b9 (\u0300hilasth\u0113ti moi, "be merciful/propitious to me") — the verb \u1f31\u03bb\u03ac\u03c3\u03ba\u03bf\u03bc\u03b1\u03b9 (hilaskomai) is the same root as the noun \u1f31\u03bb\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03ae\u03c1\u03b9\u03bf\u03bd used in Romans 3:25 for the atoning sacrifice. The tax collector is unconsciously using atonement language. \u1f04\u03c0\u03b5\u03c7\u03c9\u03bd ("standing far away") mirrors the far country of the Prodigal Son — distance as posture.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Neighbour Love and Service',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Good Samaritan',
        reference: 'Luke 10:25\u201337',
        theme: 'Love of Neighbour',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Neighbour Love and Service/The Good Samaritan.webp',
        icon: Icons.handshake_rounded,
        summary: 'A despised outsider shows mercy where the religious pass by. Who is my neighbour?',
        verse: 'But a certain Samaritan, as he travelled, came where he was. When he saw him, he was moved with compassion, came to him, and bound up his wounds, pouring on oil and wine. He set him on his own animal, and brought him to an inn, and took care of him. On the next day, when he departed, he took out two denarii, and gave them to the host, and said to him, "Take care of him. Whatever you spend beyond that, I will repay you when I return."',
        statementInBrief: 'A man is beaten and left for dead; a priest and a Levite pass by; a Samaritan stops, cares for him at cost to himself, and ensures his full recovery. Jesus redefines the question "who is my neighbour?" to "who acted like a neighbour?" — and makes a despised outsider the model of love.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The neighbour is not defined by proximity but by compassionate action',
        centralPoint: 'Jesus answers the lawyer\'s question by inverting it. Instead of "who qualifies as my neighbour (so I know where my obligation ends)," He asks "who was neighbour to the man in need?" Love of neighbour is not a boundary question — it is a posture of merciful action toward whoever is in need before you.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Who is the person in front of you right now whose need you have been walking past?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Choose one person this week whose need you have been aware of but have not acted on. Take one specific step toward them.',
          'Examine the "acceptable excuses" you use to pass by — busyness, discomfort, feeling unqualified. Bring these to God.',
          'Read Micah 6:8 alongside this parable — what does it look like to "love mercy" in your actual life?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'The lawyer asks "who is my neighbour?" to "justify himself" — to limit his obligation. Jesus\' answer refuses to provide a boundary and instead issues a command: "Go and do likewise." The parable is explicitly about action, not definition.',
        historicalContext: 'Samaritans were despised by first-century Jews as racial and religious half-breeds who had corrupted the worship of God. Choosing a Samaritan as the moral exemplar was deliberately provocative. The Jericho road was notoriously dangerous; robber attacks were common. A priest\'s avoidance may have been motivated by purity concerns — touching a corpse would render him unclean.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green and Snodgrass both note that the parable works on two levels: it defines neighbour love as cross-boundary action, and it implicitly indicts religious piety that substitutes ritual purity for human compassion. The Samaritan\'s actions are described in extraordinary detail, emphasising the personal cost and thoroughness of his mercy.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c3\u03c0\u03bb\u03b1\u03b3\u03c7\u03bd\u03af\u03c3\u03b8\u03b7 (splanchnisth\u0113, "was moved with compassion") — the same word used of the father seeing his returning son and of Jesus seeing the crowds. It is the deepest verb of compassion in the NT. \u1f10\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03ae\u03b8\u03b7\u03c4\u03b9 \u03b1\u1f50\u03c4\u03bf\u1fe6 ("take care of him") — the verb \u1f10\u03c0\u03b9\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03ad\u03bf\u03bc\u03b1\u03b9 (epimeleomai) means sustained, attentive care.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Sheep and the Goats',
        reference: 'Matthew 25:31\u201346',
        theme: 'Serving the Least',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Neighbour Love and Service/The Sheep & The Goats.webp',
        icon: Icons.people_rounded,
        summary: 'The King separates those who served the least \u2014 and Him \u2014 from those who did not.',
        verse: 'Then the King will tell those on his right hand, "Come, blessed of my Father, inherit the Kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world; for I was hungry, and you gave me food to eat. I was thirsty, and you gave me drink. I was a stranger, and you took me in."',
        statementInBrief: 'At the final judgment the King separates people as a shepherd separates sheep from goats. The criterion is astonishing: how they treated the hungry, the stranger, the sick, and the imprisoned — for in serving the least, they served the King himself.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Jesus is present in the suffering of the most vulnerable — how you treat them is how you treat Him',
        centralPoint: 'The passage\'s shocking revelation is not that service matters — it is that Jesus identifies himself with the needy. "Inasmuch as you did it to one of the least of these my brothers, you did it to me." This is not metaphor — it is identity. Service to the marginalised is encounter with Christ.',
        pdfQuestion: 'When did you last encounter Christ in someone who was hungry, lonely, sick, or imprisoned?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Commit to one regular act of service to the marginalised — a food bank, a prison visit, befriending a stranger.',
          'Read James 2:14–17 alongside this passage: faith without works is dead.',
          'Pray that God would open your eyes to see His face in the faces of those the world overlooks.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This is the climax of Matthew\'s "Olivet Discourse" — the final discourse before the Passion. It is addressed to the disciples and concerns the Son of Man\'s return in glory. It functions as the ultimate test case for the entire Sermon on the Mount: what does love of God and neighbour actually look like in practice?',
        historicalContext: 'The separation of sheep and goats at nightfall was a common Palestinian practice — sheep were kept separate from goats at night because goats needed warmth (and would huddle together, crowding sheep). The image was familiar and non-threatening, making the eschatological surprise all the more powerful.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'A major debate surrounds "the least of these my brothers" — whether "brothers" refers to all the poor, or specifically to Christian missionaries and disciples. France argues for the latter; Green and others for the universal reading. Either way, the passage radically connects Christ\'s person with human suffering.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f10\u03bb\u03ac\u03c7\u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03b9 (elachistoi, "least") is a superlative of \u03bc\u03b9\u03ba\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 — the smallest, most insignificant. Its use as an identifier for those in need is unique to this passage. The phrase \u1f10\u03c6\u02bc \u1f45\u03c3\u03bf\u03bd \u1f10\u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u03ae\u03c3\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5 \u1f11\u03bd\u1f76 \u03c4\u03bf\u03cd\u03c4\u03c9\u03bd ("inasmuch as you did it to one of these") — the singular \u1f11\u03bd\u03af is emphatic: even one act, even one person.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Rich Man and Lazarus',
        reference: 'Luke 16:19\u201331',
        theme: 'Eternal Consequences',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Neighbour Love and Service/The Rich Man & Lazarus.webp',
        icon: Icons.swap_vert_rounded,
        summary: 'A great reversal awaits. What we do with wealth and indifference has eternal consequences.',
        verse: 'Now there was a certain rich man, and he was clothed in purple and fine linen, living in luxury every day. A certain beggar, named Lazarus, was laid at his gate, full of sores, and desiring to be fed with the crumbs that fell from the rich man\'s table. Yes, even the dogs came and licked his sores.',
        statementInBrief: 'A rich man who lived in conspicuous luxury ignores a destitute man at his gate. After death, their positions are reversed: Lazarus rests with Abraham; the rich man is in torment. The parable warns that indifference to visible suffering has eternal consequences, and that no post-mortem warning system will be sent to those who ignore what they already know.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Indifference to the suffering at your door is a choice with eternal weight',
        centralPoint: 'The rich man\'s sin is not named as active cruelty but as passive indifference — Lazarus lay at his gate, visible every day. The great reversal shows that eternity takes such indifference seriously. Abraham\'s sobering response to the rich man\'s plea for a warning to be sent underlines: those who ignored Moses and the Prophets will not be moved by a resurrection.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Who is the Lazarus at your gate — the suffering person in your life who you see but pass over?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Identify one person close to you who is suffering significantly. Take one concrete step this week to alleviate their suffering.',
          'Read Amos 6:1–7 alongside this parable — the prophets already warned about indifference to the poor.',
          'Examine how you use wealth: is it building a life of comfort that walls out the needs of others?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus tells this parable immediately after the Pharisees — "who loved money" — sneer at his teaching on serving God and money (Luke 16:14). The parable confronts religious leaders who used wealth as a sign of God\'s favour and dismissed the poor as those who deserved their poverty.',
        historicalContext: 'Purple clothing was extraordinarily expensive — only the wealthiest could afford it. Lazarus (the only named character in any of Jesus\' parables) lying at a gate covered in sores was a picture of utter destitution in a culture where disgrace was attached to illness. The afterlife imagery draws on Jewish apocalyptic tradition.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green notes that Luke\'s Gospel consistently pairs warnings about wealth with reversals of status. The parable\'s ending — "if they do not hear Moses and the Prophets, neither will they be persuaded if someone rises from the dead" — is an anticipatory allusion to Jesus\' own resurrection and its rejection by those who refused to see.',
        exegeticalNotes: 'Lazarus (\u039b\u03ac\u03b6\u03b1\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2, from Hebrew \u05dc\u05b0\u05e2\u05b8\u05d6\u05b8\u05e8, El\'azar — "God helps") is the only named character in any parable of Jesus, suggesting special emphasis. The phrase \u03ba\u03cc\u03bb\u03c0\u03bf\u03c2 \u1f08\u03b2\u03c1\u03b1\u03ac\u03bc ("Abraham\'s bosom/lap") is a term of honour and intimacy — the seat of the guest of honour at a banquet.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Stewardship and Faithfulness',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Talents',
        reference: 'Matthew 25:14\u201330',
        theme: 'Faithfulness',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Stewardship and Faithfulness/The Talents.webp',
        icon: Icons.workspace_premium_rounded,
        summary: 'What we do with what God entrusts to us shapes the life we\u2019re building together with Him.',
        verse: 'For it is like a man, going into another country, who called his own servants, and entrusted his goods to them. To one he gave five talents, to another two, to another one; to each according to his own ability. Then he went on his journey.',
        statementInBrief: 'A master entrusts differing amounts to three servants according to their ability, then departs. Two invest and multiply what they received; one buries his in fear. At the master\'s return, the fruitful servants are rewarded with more responsibility; the fearful one loses everything. The parable calls for active, trusting engagement with what God has given.',
        centralPointTitle: 'God expects a return on what He has entrusted — bury nothing out of fear',
        centralPoint: 'The buried talent is not stolen — it is returned intact. Yet the master\'s response is one of fury. The sin is not squandering but fear-driven passivity. God\'s gifts are not possessions to preserve; they are resources entrusted for fruitful use on His behalf.',
        pdfQuestion: 'What has God entrusted to you that you are currently burying out of fear, self-protection, or unbelief?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'List three gifts or resources God has given you. Beside each, write one specific way you are using it for the Kingdom.',
          'Identify one area where fear is causing you to bury your talent. Pray for courage to invest it.',
          'Read 1 Corinthians 4:2 ("it is required of stewards that they be found faithful") — make this your week\'s anchor verse.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable appears in Matthew\'s Olivet Discourse alongside the Ten Virgins and the Sheep and Goats, forming a trilogy about readiness for the Kingdom\'s coming. It addresses the disciples: waiting for Jesus\' return is not passive — it demands active, faithful engagement.',
        historicalContext: 'A talent was a unit of weight (approximately 75 lbs/34 kg), used as currency — worth roughly fifteen to twenty years of a labourer\'s wages. Five talents was a truly extraordinary sum. Wealthy Romans and Jews routinely entrusted stewards with their estates during travel; the expectation of return on investment was standard practice.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France notes the deliberate contrast between faithful use and fearful burial — the parable is not about the amount given but the response. The fearful servant\'s characterisation of the master as "hard" reveals his theological misreading of God: those who see God as harsh tend toward fearful inaction rather than trusting engagement.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c4\u03ac\u03bb\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd (talanton) gives us the English word "talent" — its secondary meaning (natural ability) derives precisely from this parable. \u03b5\u1f50\u03b8\u03cd\u03c2 (euth\u0113s, "immediately") in v. 15 of the Matthean account emphasises the speed with which two of the servants go to work — immediacy is part of faithful stewardship.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Ten Minas',
        reference: 'Luke 19:11\u201327',
        theme: 'Fruitfulness',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Stewardship and Faithfulness/The Ten Minas.webp',
        icon: Icons.trending_up_rounded,
        summary: 'A nobleman gives equal gifts and expects a return. Every follower is called to fruitfulness.',
        verse: 'He said therefore, "A certain nobleman went into a far country, to receive for himself a kingdom, and to return. He called ten servants of his, and gave them ten mina coins, and told them, \'Conduct business until I come.\'"',
        statementInBrief: 'A nobleman distributes equal amounts to ten servants and commands them to put the money to work until his return. Those who multiply their minas are given authority over cities; the one who wrapped his mina in a cloth loses even that. The parable teaches that equal opportunity demands faithful engagement.',
        centralPointTitle: 'God gives everyone something to work with — fruitfulness is the expectation',
        centralPoint: 'Unlike the Talents (where amounts differ), here each servant receives the same mina. The parable removes the excuse of comparative disadvantage: the issue is not what you were given but what you did with it. Faithfulness over small things leads to authority over much.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Are you actively conducting Kingdom business with what God has given you, or have you wrapped it up and set it aside?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Take stock of your spiritual gifts, time, and resources. Write one specific way to invest each more faithfully this month.',
          'Read Luke 16:10 ("Whoever is faithful in very little is also faithful in much") as a companion verse.',
          'Pray: "Lord, show me what I have wrapped up out of fear, comfort, or distraction."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus tells this parable as He approaches Jerusalem, "because they supposed that the Kingdom of God was going to appear immediately" (Luke 19:11). He corrects that expectation: there will be an interval — a time of service and faithfulness — before the King returns in glory.',
        historicalContext: 'The political subplot (citizens who hate the nobleman and send a delegation against him) likely alludes to historical events: Archelaus, son of Herod the Great, went to Rome to receive his kingdom while a Jewish delegation tried to prevent it. Jesus\' original hearers would have recognised the context.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green (NICNT) reads the parable as fundamentally about discipleship in the in-between time: between Jesus\' departure and return, followers are called to active, productive engagement with the Kingdom\'s concerns. The political subplot introduces a note of judgment against those who openly reject the king.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c0\u03c1\u03b1\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1\u03c4\u03b5\u03cd\u03c3\u03b1\u03c3\u03b8\u03b5 (\u0300pragmateusasthe, "conduct business") — from \u03c0\u03c1\u1fb6\u03b3\u03bc\u03b1 (pragma, "deed/thing done") — an active commercial term meaning to trade or do business. The command is not abstract but practical and businesslike. \u03c3\u03bf\u03c5\u03b4\u03b1\u03c1\u03af\u1ff3 (\u0300soudari\u014d, "in a cloth/napkin") indicates careless storage rather than intentional burial — perhaps even more damning.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Unjust Steward',
        reference: 'Luke 16:1\u201313',
        theme: 'Eternal Wisdom',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Stewardship and Faithfulness/The Unjust Steward.webp',
        icon: Icons.calculate_rounded,
        summary: 'A manager acts shrewdly for his future. Jesus calls us to be equally strategic about eternity.',
        verse: 'His lord commended the dishonest manager because he had done wisely, for the children of this world are, in their own generation, wiser than the children of the light. I tell you, make for yourselves friends by means of unrighteous mammon, so that when you fail, they may receive you into the eternal tents.',
        statementInBrief: 'A dishonest manager, about to be fired, quickly reduces the debts of his master\'s debtors to secure his future. His master commends his shrewdness. Jesus does not commend his dishonesty but his strategic urgency: use what you have now to prepare for what comes next.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Use worldly wealth with Kingdom wisdom — your choices now have eternal implications',
        centralPoint: 'This is Jesus\' most difficult parable. He does not endorse the manager\'s fraud; he commends the shrewdness — the urgent, creative, strategic use of available resources for a coming reality. Disciples should be as strategic about eternity as worldly people are about their immediate futures.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Are you using what you have now — money, relationships, time — with the same urgency for eternal purposes that people use for earthly ones?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Review your financial giving: does it reflect Kingdom priorities with the urgency of someone who takes eternity seriously?',
          'Identify one relationship that could become a bridge to the Kingdom — invest in it specifically this month.',
          'Read 1 Timothy 6:17–19 alongside this parable: the call to "store up treasure for the future."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus addresses this to "his disciples" (16:1) — distinct from the Pharisees who are overhearing. The parable is deliberately shocking: the commended character is a rogue. Jesus uses moral ambiguity to force his disciples to think carefully about what strategic faithfulness actually looks like.',
        historicalContext: 'Stewards in the ancient world managed estates and could make financial arrangements on behalf of their masters. The reductions in debt may represent the removal of interest charges (which was sometimes added to the principal and was technically illegal under Jewish law) — the steward may have been "correcting" inflated accounts, making his actions legally complicated.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'This is widely regarded as the hardest parable in the Gospels. Green argues the commendation is strictly limited to the shrewdness, not the ethics. Snodgrass reads it as a call to "Kingdom entrepreneurship" — using what is available now for what matters eternally. The master\'s commendation is genuine surprise at the servant\'s resourcefulness.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c6\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03bc\u03c9\u03c2 (phronimos, "shrewdly/wisely") — this is the same word used of the wise bridesmaids in Matthew 25. It describes strategic, prudent forward-thinking. \u03bc\u03b1\u03bc\u03c9\u03bd\u1fb6 (mammon) — an Aramaic loanword for wealth; Jesus uses it without endorsing it, treating it as a category of resource to be used wisely rather than trusted in.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Rich Fool',
        reference: 'Luke 12:16\u201321',
        theme: 'True Wealth',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Stewardship and Faithfulness/The Rich Fool.webp',
        icon: Icons.savings_rounded,
        summary: 'Bigger barns, no eternity. What does it mean to be rich toward God rather than yourself?',
        verse: 'The ground of a certain rich man produced abundantly. He reasoned within himself, saying, "What will I do, because I don\'t have room to store my crops?" He said, "This is what I will do. I will pull down my barns, and build bigger ones, and there I will store all my grain and my goods. I will tell my soul, \'Soul, you have many goods laid up for many years. Take your ease, eat, drink, be merry.\'" But God said to him, "You fool! Tonight your soul is required of you. The things which you have prepared—whose will they be?"',
        statementInBrief: 'A successful farmer faces a surplus and resolves it with a building project. His entire monologue is self-referential — "I," "my," "myself" appears twelve times. God interrupts with the one thing the farmer has not considered: death. Accumulation without God is the definition of folly.',
        centralPointTitle: 'True security is being rich toward God, not rich in things',
        centralPoint: 'The farmer is not condemned for his productivity but for what he does with it: he builds a life entirely around self-provision and self-satisfaction, with no reference to God or to others. The sudden divine announcement — "your soul is required of you tonight" — exposes the fragility of security built on barns.',
        pdfQuestion: 'What is the "bigger barn" you are building — the thing you are counting on to give you security and peace?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Write out a personal financial philosophy in light of this parable: what does "rich toward God" look like in your specific situation?',
          'Fast from purchases or consumption for three days and use the money given to someone who has genuine need.',
          'Read Ecclesiastes 2:1–11 alongside this parable — the Preacher arrives at the same conclusion from a lifetime of excess.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Someone in the crowd asks Jesus to settle an inheritance dispute. Jesus refuses — "who made me a judge or arbitrator over you?" — and immediately tells this parable. The context: the man\'s preoccupation is wealth; Jesus\' response is to expose the poverty of wealth-centred life.',
        historicalContext: 'Storing grain in Palestine was essential for years of poor harvest. The farmer\'s response to abundance — build bigger storage — was entirely rational by economic standards. The parable\'s critique is not of the prudence but of the exclusive orientation of his life toward self-provision.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green (NICNT) notes the irony: this farmer has solved the problem of abundance perfectly — by his own lights. Jesus labels him \u1f04\u03c6\u03c1\u03c9\u03bd (aphron, "fool") — not in the sense of stupidity but in the biblical sense of the one who lives as if God does not exist (Ps 14:1). The parable does not prohibit saving; it diagnoses the self-sufficiency that excludes God.',
        exegeticalNotes: 'The internal monologue in vv. 17–19 uses first-person pronouns and possessives eleven or twelve times — the structural self-absorption is mirrored in the language itself. \u03c0\u03bb\u03bf\u03c5\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bd \u03b5\u1f30\u03c2 \u03b8\u03b5\u03cc\u03bd (ploutein eis theon, "rich toward God") — this unique phrase appears only here; it means investing in what has eternal currency rather than temporal storage.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Prayer and Persistence',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Persistent Widow',
        reference: 'Luke 18:1\u20138',
        theme: 'Persevering Prayer',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Prayer and Persistence/The Persistent Widow.webp',
        icon: Icons.record_voice_over_rounded,
        summary: 'A widow keeps coming. God hears those who cry to Him day and night \u2014 and He will act.',
        verse: 'There was a judge in a city who didn\'t fear God, and didn\'t respect man. A widow was in that city, and she often came to him, saying, "Defend me from my adversary!" He wouldn\'t for a while, but afterward he said to himself, "Though I neither fear God, nor respect man, yet because this widow bothers me, I will defend her, so that she doesn\'t wear me out by her continual coming."',
        statementInBrief: 'A widow repeatedly petitions an unjust judge until he grants her justice — not out of righteousness but to stop being pestered. If an unjust judge responds to persistence, how much more will a just and loving God respond to his people\'s cries? Luke\'s framing is explicit: this parable is about praying without giving up.',
        centralPointTitle: 'If an unjust judge yields to persistence, how much more will a just God answer those who cry to Him?',
        centralPoint: 'The parable argues from the lesser to the greater: if even a corrupt judge eventually grants justice to avoid being worn out, then God — who is righteous, loving, and attentive — will certainly vindicate those who cry to him. The question in v. 8 is the sting: "will the Son of Man find faith on earth when he comes?"',
        pdfQuestion: 'Where have you stopped praying because you assumed God wasn\'t listening — and will you come back to that request?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Identify one long-held prayer request you have drifted from. Commit to bringing it to God daily for thirty days.',
          'Read Romans 8:26–27 alongside this parable: the Spirit intercedes for us — we are not alone in our persistence.',
          'Examine what "giving up" on prayer reveals about your theology of God. What do you actually believe He is like?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Luke frames the parable explicitly (18:1): "he told them a parable to show that they should always pray and not lose heart." The disciples are facing the prospect of opposition, delay, and God\'s apparent silence. Jesus addresses their discouragement directly.',
        historicalContext: 'Widows in first-century Palestine had no male advocate and were socially and legally vulnerable. A judge who "feared neither God nor man" was one who operated outside the covenantal framework of justice Israel expected. The widow\'s persistence against such a figure was an act of extraordinary courage.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green notes the careful contrast: the judge is godless and self-interested; God is righteous and attentive. The argument is a fortiori — from the worse to the better. The final question in v. 8 suggests the real concern is not whether God will answer, but whether his people will persist in faith long enough to receive it.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f10\u03ba\u03b4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bd (\u0300ekdikein, "vindicate/defend") — a legal term for upholding someone\'s legal rights. \u1f51\u03c0\u03c9\u03c0\u03b9\u03ac\u03b6\u03b7 (hyp\u014dpiaz\u0113, "wear me out/give me a black eye") — the verb literally means to strike under the eye; colloquially, to wear someone down. The judge fears being utterly exhausted by her persistence.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Friend at Midnight',
        reference: 'Luke 11:5\u20138',
        theme: 'Boldness in Prayer',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Prayer and Persistence/The Friend at Midnight.webp',
        icon: Icons.nights_stay_rounded,
        summary: 'Shameless persistence in asking unlocks what reluctance alone would not. Keep asking.',
        verse: '"I tell you, although he will not rise and give it to him because he is his friend, yet because of his shameless persistence, he will get up and give him as many as he needs. I tell you, keep asking, and it will be given you. Keep seeking, and you will find. Keep knocking, and it will be opened to you."',
        statementInBrief: 'A man wakes his friend at midnight to borrow bread for an unexpected guest. The friend refuses initially — his family is in bed. But the man\'s shameless persistence wins out. Jesus connects this to prayer: ask, seek, knock — keep doing it — and God will answer.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Come to God with shameless, bold persistence — He is more willing than any reluctant friend',
        centralPoint: 'The Greek word \u1f00\u03bd\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 (anaideia) does not mean "importunity" (as traditionally translated) but "shamelessness" or "boldness." The friend succeeds not because he wears the sleeper down but because he comes without shame — with confidence that his need will be met. This is the model for prayer.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Do you come to God in prayer with boldness and confidence, or do you hold back out of a sense that your needs are too much?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Choose three requests you have been hesitant to bring to God because they seem too big or too small. Bring them boldly this week.',
          'Memorise Luke 11:9–10 ("keep asking... keep seeking... keep knocking") and let it be your posture in prayer.',
          'Read Hebrews 4:16 alongside this parable: we approach the throne of grace with confidence, not shame.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable comes immediately after Jesus teaches the Lord\'s Prayer (Luke 11:1–4). It is an explanation of the posture that should accompany that prayer — not reluctance or doubt, but bold, expectant persistence.',
        historicalContext: 'In first-century Palestinian villages, homes were single-room; the whole family slept on a raised platform together. Getting up in the middle of the night meant disturbing everyone. Hospitality obligations were sacred — failure to provide for a guest brought shame on the whole community.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green and Snodgrass both support the reading of \u1f00\u03bd\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 (anaideia) as "shamelessness" (i.e., boldness of approach) rather than persistence, following the work of Joachim Jeremias. The point is that the boldness of the asker — not the wearing down of the giver — is the model for prayer.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f00\u03bd\u03b1\u03af\u03b4\u03b5\u03b9\u03b1 (anaideia) appears only here in the NT. It is the opposite of \u03b1\u1f30\u03b4\u03ce\u03c2 (aid\u014ds, "shame/reserve") — it means coming without shame or embarrassment. The present imperatives in v. 9 — \u03b1\u1f30\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c4\u03b5... \u03b6\u03b7\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c4\u03b5... \u03ba\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5 — indicate continuous, ongoing action: "keep asking... keep seeking... keep knocking."',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Readiness and Watchfulness',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Ten Virgins',
        reference: 'Matthew 25:1\u201313',
        theme: 'Readiness',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Readiness and Watchfulness/The Ten Virgins.webp',
        icon: Icons.lightbulb_rounded,
        summary: 'Five prepared, five not. Stay ready \u2014 you do not know the day or the hour.',
        verse: 'Then the Kingdom of Heaven will be like ten virgins, who took their lamps, and went out to meet the bridegroom. Five of them were foolish, and five were wise. Those who were foolish, when they took their lamps, took no oil with them, but the wise took oil in their vessels with their lamps. Now while the bridegroom delayed, they all slumbered and slept.',
        statementInBrief: 'Ten bridesmaids go out to meet the bridegroom. Five bring extra oil; five do not. When the bridegroom is delayed and they all fall asleep, the wise are ready when he arrives at midnight; the foolish are not. The door is shut. The parable calls for a readiness that is sustained, not last-minute.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Readiness for the Kingdom cannot be borrowed at the last moment',
        centralPoint: 'The foolish virgins are not wicked — they are unprepared. They assumed they had enough; they did not plan for delay. The oil cannot be transferred: you cannot borrow another person\'s relationship with God, their spiritual depth, or their readiness when the moment comes.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Is your spiritual life built for a long wait — or are you living as though the bridegroom must arrive on your schedule?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Review your spiritual disciplines: are they building depth and sustained readiness, or are they sporadic and crisis-driven?',
          'Read Revelation 19:7–8 alongside this parable — the bride makes herself ready. What does that look like for you today?',
          'Pray: "Lord, I want to be found ready. Show me where I am unprepared and fill me with Your Spirit."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable opens Matthew 25\'s trilogy of Kingdom preparedness, addressed to the disciples on the Mount of Olives after their question about the end of the age. The delay of the bridegroom represents the extended period between Jesus\' resurrection and return.',
        historicalContext: 'Jewish wedding processions took place at night, with the groom coming to fetch the bride from her father\'s house. Torches or oil lamps were essential for the procession and the celebration. The length of the delay was unpredictable — guests had to be prepared to wait.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France reads this as a parable of personal responsibility for spiritual preparedness that cannot be transferred. The shut door (v. 10) and "I do not know you" (v. 12) echo Matthew 7:21–23 — the judgment scene at the sermon\'s end. Readiness is not a single act but a sustained posture.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c6\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03b9 (phronimoi, "wise") and \u03bc\u03c9\u03c1\u03b1\u03af (m\u014drai, "foolish") appear together in Matthew 7:24–27 (Wise and Foolish Builders), linking the two parables. \u03b5\u1f30\u03c2 \u03c4\u1f70\u03c2 \u1f00\u03b3\u03b3\u03b5\u1fd6\u03b1 ("into the vessels") — extra oil kept in separate vessels for the journey; the foolish assumed their initial supply was sufficient.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Thief in the Night',
        reference: 'Matthew 24:42\u201344',
        theme: 'Watchfulness',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Readiness and Watchfulness/The Thief in the Night.webp',
        icon: Icons.visibility_rounded,
        summary: 'No one knows when the Son of Man is coming. Watchfulness is not optional.',
        verse: 'Watch therefore, for you don\'t know in what hour your Lord comes. But know this, that if the master of the house had known in what watch of the night the thief was coming, he would have watched, and would not have allowed his house to be broken into. Therefore also be ready, for in an hour that you don\'t expect, the Son of Man will come.',
        statementInBrief: 'No homeowner would sleep through a known burglary. The point is the unexpectedness: if you knew when the thief was coming, you would be awake. Because you do not know when the Son of Man returns, watchfulness must be permanent — not a response to warning but a state of life.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Because the hour is unknown, watchfulness must be constant',
        centralPoint: 'This brief parable is essentially an argument from analogy: the same logic that makes a homeowner stay awake when burglary is a possibility should make the disciple maintain a posture of readiness for the Son of Man\'s return. Not an anxious alertness, but an oriented, prepared life.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Would you live any differently today if you knew Jesus was returning tomorrow? Why aren\'t you living that way now?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'For one week, begin each morning with the prayer: "Lord, I live this day ready for You."',
          'Identify one habit or pattern in your life that you would change if you knew Jesus was coming this year. Change it now.',
          'Read 1 Thessalonians 5:1–11 alongside this parable: live as "children of the light" rather than of darkness.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This comes within the Olivet Discourse as Jesus responds to the disciples\' question about signs of the end. His answer consistently is: the timing is not yours to know; therefore be always ready. The parable moves from information-seeking to posture-forming.',
        historicalContext: 'Night-watches in first-century Palestine were divided into four periods. A thief would choose the most unexpected hour. The master of the house\'s vulnerability is not weakness but ignorance of timing — which is Jesus\' precise point about the disciples\' situation.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France reads this as a deliberately anti-speculative parable: the appropriate response to ignorance of the timing is not calculation but watchfulness. The thief image, used of the Son of Man\'s return, recurs in 1 Thess 5:2, 2 Pet 3:10, and Rev 3:3, showing it became an early Christian idiom for unexpected divine visitation.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03b3\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03bf\u03c1\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c4\u03b5 (gr\u0113goreite, "watch/be alert") — present imperative: an ongoing command, not a one-time act. The verb is used in Gethsemane (Matt 26:38) — Jesus commands watchfulness while his disciples fail at it. \u1f10\u03b3\u03c1\u03b7\u03b3\u03cc\u03c1\u03b7\u03c3\u03b5\u03bd (\u0300egr\u0113gor\u0113sen, "would have watched") is an aorist indicative — a specific action that would have happened had the information been available.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Faithful and Unfaithful Servants',
        reference: 'Matthew 24:45\u201351',
        theme: 'Faithful Service',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Readiness and Watchfulness/The Faithful and Unfaithful Servants.webp',
        icon: Icons.manage_accounts_rounded,
        summary: 'The master returns and finds either faithful service or self-indulgence. What will He find in you?',
        verse: '"Who then is the faithful and wise servant, whom his lord has set over his household, to give them their food in due season? Blessed is that servant whom his lord finds so doing when he comes. Most certainly I tell you that he will set him over all that he has. But if that evil servant should say in his heart, \'My lord is delayed,\' and begins to beat his fellow servants, and eat and drink with the drunkards, the lord of that servant will come in a day when he doesn\'t expect it."',
        statementInBrief: 'One servant continues faithful service in the master\'s absence; another assumes the master\'s absence is an opportunity for self-indulgence and abuse. When the master returns unexpectedly, the contrast in response determines their eternal futures. Watchfulness expresses itself in faithfulness, not in calculation.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Readiness for the master\'s return means faithful service during His absence',
        centralPoint: 'The evil servant\'s error is not a single bad act but a single bad assumption: "my master is delayed" — which becomes a license for self-rule. Watchfulness is demonstrated not by predicting when the master returns, but by serving faithfully as if he might arrive at any moment.',
        pdfQuestion: 'In what area of your life are you behaving as though the Master is absent and unlikely to return soon?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'For one week, perform your work — every task, every relationship — as if the Master were watching and arriving today.',
          'Identify one place where the assumption "God is far away or delayed" has crept into your behaviour. Repent and reorient.',
          'Read Colossians 3:23–24 alongside this parable: "work heartily, as for the Lord and not for men."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Immediately following the Thief in the Night parable, this one applies the watchfulness command to specific behaviour: faithful service to others in the master\'s household. The question "who then is the faithful and wise servant?" is rhetorical — it invites self-examination.',
        historicalContext: 'Household managers in large estates held real authority — feeding, organising, and managing others. The management of a household in the master\'s absence was a serious responsibility that could be honoured or abused. Physical abuse of fellow servants (beating them) was a legal and social offence.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France sees this parable as completing the Olivet Discourse\'s answer to "how should we live while waiting?" The answer is: the same way you would live if the master were present — faithfully, accountably, attentively. The contrast with the evil servant is a warning against assuming grace buys time for self-indulgence.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c6\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 (phronimos, "wise") links this to the Wise Virgins (Matt 25) and the Wise Builder (Matt 7) — a thread through Matthew\'s parables. \u03c7\u03c1\u03bf\u03bd\u03af\u03b6\u03b5\u03b9 (\u0300chronizei, "is delayed") — from \u03c7\u03c1\u03cc\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 (chronos, time); the assumption of delay is itself the corruption that enables the servant\'s self-indulgence.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Invitation and Response',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Great Banquet',
        reference: 'Luke 14:15\u201324',
        theme: 'Receiving the Call',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Invitation and Response/The Great Banquet.webp',
        icon: Icons.dinner_dining_rounded,
        summary: 'The invited make excuses; the outsiders fill the seats. No one who rejects God\u2019s call should assume they belong at His table.',
        verse: 'He said to him, "A certain man made a great supper, and he invited many people. He sent out his servant at supper time to tell those who were invited, \'Come, for everything is ready now.\' They all as one began to make excuses."',
        statementInBrief: 'Guests invited to a great banquet make excuses; the host fills his table with the poor, crippled, blind, and lame — then sends out to the roads and hedges for strangers. The original invitees are excluded. The Kingdom of God is opened wider than its first recipients expect, and their refusal is not neutral.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The invitation is open wide — but refusal has permanent consequences',
        centralPoint: 'The excuses are reasonable-sounding (a field, oxen, a new marriage) but they represent the choice of present concerns over an extraordinary invitation. Jesus\' parable warns: those who assume their place at God\'s table while postponing the commitment to be there will find themselves excluded — and others in their seats.',
        pdfQuestion: 'What reasonable excuse are you using to delay wholehearted response to God\'s call?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Examine your daily schedule: what takes priority over God\'s invitation to seek first his Kingdom?',
          'Read Isaiah 25:6–8 alongside this parable — the great banquet is the fulfilment of Israel\'s hope.',
          'Pray for those currently outside the invited circle — your neighbourhood, your city — and ask how you participate in God\'s wider invitation.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus tells this parable at a Pharisee\'s dinner (Luke 14:1) after observing the guests jostling for seats of honour. It responds to a pious comment: "Blessed is the one who eats bread in the Kingdom of God!" Jesus turns pious assumption into searching challenge: who will actually be there?',
        historicalContext: 'Formal banquets in the ancient world involved two invitations: an advance notice and a same-day summons when the meal was ready. Refusing the second invitation — after accepting the first — was a serious social insult. Jesus\' hearers would have understood the depth of the offence.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green reads the list of replacements — poor, crippled, blind, lame — as echoing the list of those Jesus says will be blessed when invited to meals (Luke 14:13). The parable thus enacts Jesus\' own teaching. The "roads and hedges" invitation extends to Gentiles in Luke\'s wider narrative.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c0\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03b9\u03c4\u03b5\u1fd6\u03c3\u03b8\u03b1\u03b9 (paraiteisthai, "to make excuses/decline") — the same verb is used in Heb 12:19 for Israel refusing God at Sinai. The three excuses share a structure: something acquired, something owned, something contracted — earthly ties that seemed more immediate than the divine invitation.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Wedding Banquet',
        reference: 'Matthew 22:1\u201314',
        theme: 'Worthy Response',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Invitation and Response/The Wedding Banquet.webp',
        icon: Icons.celebration_rounded,
        summary: 'A king\u2019s feast is refused and rejected. The invitation is opened wide \u2014 but being found without the right garment is still fatal.',
        verse: 'The Kingdom of Heaven is like a certain king, who made a marriage feast for his son, and sent out his servants to call those who were invited to the marriage feast, but they would not come. He sent out other servants, saying, "Tell those who are invited, \'Behold, I have prepared my dinner. My bulls and my fatlings are killed, and all things are ready. Come to the marriage feast!\'"',
        statementInBrief: 'A king holds a wedding banquet for his son; the invited guests refuse and abuse the messengers. The king opens the invitation to all — good and bad alike — filling the hall. But one guest arrives without a wedding garment and is cast out. Both refusal and insufficient response are addressed: the invitation is wide, but it demands a real change.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The invitation is wide open — but it calls for a transformed response, not mere presence',
        centralPoint: 'The man without the wedding garment is not uninvited — he came in. But he came on his own terms, without the transformation the occasion demands. The parable warns that accepting the invitation is not enough; the garment — righteousness, transformation, real discipleship — is required.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Have you accepted God\'s invitation while remaining unchanged — attending without being transformed?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Read Revelation 19:7–8 — "the fine linen is the righteous deeds of the saints." What is your wedding garment made of?',
          'Ask honestly: am I in the banquet hall but living on my own terms? Bring that honestly to God.',
          'Memorise Matthew 22:14 — "many are called, but few are chosen" — and let it prompt daily examination.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Matthew places this parable after the Triumphal Entry and amid escalating conflict with the chief priests and Pharisees. The violence of the invited guests toward the messengers and the king\'s military response (vv. 6–7) allude to the destruction of Jerusalem — this parable is more confrontational than its Lukan parallel.',
        historicalContext: 'Wedding garments were sometimes provided by the host for guests who could not afford their own — the man\'s lack of one suggests wilful refusal to put it on, not poverty. The binding hand and foot and casting into outer darkness escalates the stakes beyond Luke\'s version, emphasising the severity of unprepared response.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France reads the two-stage rejection (those originally invited, then the man without the garment) as targeting two different failures: outright rejection of the gospel and nominal Christianity without genuine transformation. Both are addressed in the same parable.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03b7\u03c1\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b5 \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u1f00\u03b3\u03b1\u03b8\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 (pon\u0113rous te kai agathous, "both bad and good") — the invitation is morally indiscriminate. \u1f14\u03bd\u03b4\u03c5\u03bc\u03b1 \u03b3\u03ac\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5 (endyma gamou, "wedding garment") — only here in the NT; the specificity suggests this was a recognised cultural requirement. \u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03c9\u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 (\u0300keph\u014dmenos, "muzzled/speechless") — the man is silenced; he has no defence.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Two Sons',
        reference: 'Matthew 21:28\u201332',
        theme: 'True Obedience',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Invitation and Response/The Two Sons.webp',
        icon: Icons.people_alt_rounded,
        summary: 'One says yes and does nothing; one says no and repents. Actions, not words, define obedience.',
        verse: '"But what do you think? A man had two sons, and he came to the first, and said, \'Son, go work today in my vineyard.\' He answered, \'I will not,\' but afterward he changed his mind, and went. He came to the second, and said the same thing. He answered, \'I go, sir,\' but he didn\'t go. Which of the two did the will of his father?"',
        statementInBrief: 'One son says no and then repents and goes to work; the other says yes and does nothing. Jesus asks which one did the father\'s will and his interlocutors answer correctly — then he applies it directly: tax collectors and prostitutes who repented are entering the Kingdom ahead of the religious leaders who said yes without following through.',
        centralPointTitle: 'Declared obedience without action is not obedience — repented refusal followed by action is',
        centralPoint: 'Jesus uses a simple story to expose the gap between verbal compliance and genuine discipleship. The son who said "I go" and did not is a portrait of religious profession without transformation. The son who said "I will not" but repented is the model for those outside the religious establishment who responded to John\'s message.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Where in your life have you said "yes, Lord" and then done nothing — or said "no" and repented?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Identify one specific command of Jesus you have verbally affirmed but not actually obeyed. Take one concrete step toward it this week.',
          'Read James 1:22–25 alongside this parable: "be doers of the word, not hearers only."',
          'Examine your use of religious language: are your "yes, Lords" followed by actual changes of direction?',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus tells this parable directly to the chief priests and elders who have challenged his authority (Matt 21:23). It is a pointed rebuke: they are the son who says yes and does nothing. The tax collectors and prostitutes who followed John\'s preaching are the son who said no but repented.',
        historicalContext: 'The vineyard was a central image of Israel in the OT (Isa 5:1–7); sending sons to work in it carried immediate resonance. The authority Jesus claimed — and which the religious leaders challenged — is precisely what the parable defends: those who respond to God\'s call are the ones with standing, not those who claim institutional authority.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France notes that this parable, together with the Tenants (Matt 21:33–46), forms a pair of vineyard parables that escalate the indictment of the religious leadership. Both make the same point: stated allegiance is worthless without the fruit of obedience.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bc\u03b5\u03bb\u03b7\u03b8\u03b5\u03af\u03c2 (metamel\u0113theis, "changed his mind/repented") — a different verb from \u03bc\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03bd\u03bf\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bd (metanoein); it carries the sense of emotional regret leading to change of action. \u03c4\u03af \u03b4\u1f72 \u1f51\u03bc\u1fd6\u03bd \u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03b5\u1fd6 ("what do you think?") is Matthew\'s characteristic introduction to pronouncement parables — it invites the audience to pronounce their own judgment.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Wicked Tenants',
        reference: 'Matthew 21:33\u201346',
        theme: 'Bearing Fruit',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Invitation and Response/The Wicked Tenants.webp',
        icon: Icons.agriculture_rounded,
        summary: 'Tenants refuse to return what belongs to the owner. The Kingdom will be given to those who bear its fruit.',
        verse: 'There was a man who was a master of a household, who planted a vineyard, set a hedge about it, dug a winepress in it, built a tower, leased it out to farmers, and went into another country. When the season for the fruit came near, he sent his servants to the farmers, to receive his fruit. The farmers took his servants, beat one, killed another, and stoned another.',
        statementInBrief: 'Tenants in a vineyard beat and kill the owner\'s messengers and finally kill his son, assuming the inheritance will be theirs. The owner destroys them and gives the vineyard to others. The parable is Jesus\' most direct confrontation of the religious leadership: Israel\'s leaders have failed their stewardship and the Kingdom will be given to those who bear its fruit.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The Kingdom\'s fruit belongs to those who produce it — not to those who claim custody of the vineyard',
        centralPoint: 'The tenants mistake custody for ownership. They have been given stewardship of the vineyard — Israel\'s covenant life — but they produce nothing for the owner and violently resist his claims. The "son" they kill is transparently Jesus; the outcome is judgment and the transfer of the Kingdom to those who will be fruitful.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Have you confused religious position, tradition, or membership with genuine fruitfulness? What fruit is God looking for from your life?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Read Isaiah 5:1–7 alongside this parable — Jesus deliberately echoes the Song of the Vineyard as judgment on failed stewardship.',
          'Examine your life for the fruit of the Kingdom: love, justice, mercy, evangelism, discipleship. Where is fruit being produced?',
          'Pray: "Lord, make me a fruitful steward of everything you have entrusted to me."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'The chief priests and Pharisees "perceived that he was speaking about them" (Matt 21:45) — Jesus does not veil this parable. It is placed after his cleansing of the Temple and amid his escalating confrontation with the religious establishment in his final week before the crucifixion.',
        historicalContext: 'The vineyard image comes directly from Isaiah 5 — a well-known passage about God\'s judgment on unfaithful Israel. First-century Palestine had many absentee landlords whose estates were managed by tenant farmers. The escalating violence (servants beaten, killed, stoned, and finally the son killed) mirrors Israel\'s treatment of the prophets.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France notes the parable is so transparent that it functions almost as an allegory: the owner is God, the vineyard is Israel, the servants are the prophets, and the son is Jesus. Yet its form is still parabolic — inviting the hearers to pronounce their own judgment before Jesus applies it.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03bb\u03b9\u03b8\u03bf\u03b2\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c3\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b5\u03c2 \u1f00\u03c0\u03ad\u03ba\u03c4\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd (lithobol\u0113santes apekteinan, "stoning and killing") — stoning was the prescribed OT punishment for blasphemy; the tenants treat the owner\'s messengers as blasphemers against their own authority. \u03ba\u03b5\u03c6\u03b1\u03bb\u1f74\u03bd \u03b3\u03c9\u03bd\u03af\u03b1\u03c2 (kephal\u0113n g\u014dnias, "cornerstone") in v. 42 quotes Psalm 118:22 — the stone the builders rejected becomes the chief cornerstone.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Grace and Reward',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Workers in the Vineyard',
        reference: 'Matthew 20:1\u201316',
        theme: 'God\u2019s Generosity',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Grace & Reward/Workers.webp',
        icon: Icons.agriculture_rounded,
        summary: 'All receive the same wage regardless of hours worked. God\u2019s generosity is not governed by human fairness.',
        verse: 'For the Kingdom of Heaven is like a man who was the master of a household, who went out early in the morning to hire laborers for his vineyard. When he had agreed with the laborers for a denarius a day, he sent them into his vineyard.',
        statementInBrief: 'Workers hired throughout the day all receive the same wage at evening — a full denarius each. Those who worked longest complain of unfairness. The landowner\'s response is definitive: I gave you what I promised; am I not allowed to be generous with my own? God\'s grace does not follow human economics.',
        centralPointTitle: 'God\'s generosity is not governed by human calculations of fairness',
        centralPoint: 'The parable offends our instinct for proportional reward. But the point is not that effort is irrelevant — it is that God\'s generosity toward those who come late is not a subtraction from those who came early. Envy at another\'s grace is a failure to understand the nature of grace itself.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Do you resent God\'s generosity toward someone who seems to have "done less" than you? What does that reveal about your understanding of grace?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Reflect on someone whose experience of grace or blessing you have envied. Repent of comparing, and celebrate their blessing.',
          'Read Romans 11:33–36 alongside this parable — God\'s ways are not our ways, and His judgments are unsearchable.',
          'Pray: "Lord, make me a person who celebrates the latecomer\'s grace as much as my own."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable immediately follows Peter\'s question: "We have left everything and followed you. What then will we have?" (Matt 19:27). The parable is a gentle correction: the Kingdom\'s reward logic is not the marketplace\'s logic. It is framed by "the last will be first, and the first last" (19:30; 20:16).',
        historicalContext: 'Day labourers in first-century Palestine were typically hired at dawn in the marketplace, surviving day to day. A denarius was a standard day\'s wage. Those hired late in the day were likely those who had not been chosen earlier — perhaps older, weaker, or less skilled. Receiving a full day\'s wage was extraordinary generosity.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France reads the parable as primarily about the freedom of God\'s grace rather than about the relative merits of early and late disciples. The householder\'s question — "Is your eye evil because I am good?" — invokes the "evil eye" (envy) as the moral failure in view. The resentful workers have received exactly what they were promised; their complaint is about others\' receipt of grace.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f60\u03c6\u03b8\u03b1\u03bb\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c3\u03bf\u03c5 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bd\u03b7\u03c1\u03cc\u03c2 (\u0300ophthalmos sou pon\u0113ros, "is your eye evil?") — this is an idiom for envy or stinginess. The "evil eye" is the opposite of the "good eye" (generosity), as in Matt 6:22–23. \u1f43 \u03b8\u03ad\u03bb\u03c9 \u03b4\u1f71\u03bd\u03b1\u03b9 ("what I will, I give") — the landowner\'s sovereignty in generosity is deliberately absolute.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Two Debtors',
        reference: 'Luke 7:41\u201343',
        theme: 'Love and Forgiveness',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Grace & Reward/TwoDebtors.webp',
        icon: Icons.favorite_border_rounded,
        summary: 'The one forgiven most loves most. Do you understand how much you have been forgiven?',
        verse: '"A certain lender had two debtors. The one owed five hundred denarii, and the other fifty. When they couldn\'t pay, he forgave them both. Which of them therefore will love him most?" Simon answered, "He, I suppose, to whom he forgave the most." He said to him, "You have judged correctly."',
        statementInBrief: 'A moneylender forgives two unequal debts; the one forgiven the greater amount loves the more. Jesus applies this directly to the woman who has anointed him versus Simon the Pharisee: her extravagant love flows from extravagant forgiveness received; Simon\'s cold hospitality reveals he has not truly understood how much he himself needs.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The depth of your love for God is measured by your grasp of how much you have been forgiven',
        centralPoint: 'This miniature parable is Jesus\' answer to Simon\'s unspoken judgment of the sinful woman. Her love is not the cause of forgiveness — it is the evidence of it. And Simon\'s tepid love is not the cause of his greater righteousness — it is the evidence that he does not truly see himself as a debtor.',
        pdfQuestion: 'Do you love God with the intensity of someone who has been forgiven a vast debt — or with the coolness of someone who does not think they owe much?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Sit with the specific sins God has forgiven you. Write a prayer of gratitude that names them honestly.',
          'Read 1 Timothy 1:15–16 (Paul\'s self-identification as "chief of sinners") — how does knowing your debt shape your love?',
          'Look for someone who loves God extravagantly. Instead of being uncomfortable, ask what it might mean for you.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'A woman described as a "sinner" (likely a known prostitute) enters Simon\'s dining room and anoints Jesus\' feet with tears and perfume. Simon\'s internal judgment that Jesus should have known what kind of woman she is provides the parable\'s setting and target.',
        historicalContext: 'Five hundred denarii was approximately twenty months\' wages; fifty was two months\'. Neither was payable for someone in poverty. The cancellation of both was pure generosity, with no distinction made on grounds of the debt\'s size — both were fully released.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green (NICNT) reads the parable as a challenge to the honour system that placed Pharisees near God and sinners at the margins. Jesus\' pronouncement that the woman\'s sins "are forgiven" (using the divine passive, confirming God\'s forgiveness) is the climax — but the parable\'s logic sets it up.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c7\u03b1\u03c1\u03b9\u03c3\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03bf\u03c2 (charissamenos, "he forgave/graciously gave") — from \u03c7\u03ac\u03c1\u03b9\u03c2 (charis, grace); the debt cancellation is explicitly an act of grace, not earned. \u03c0\u03bb\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03bd \u1f00\u03b3\u03b1\u03c0\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03b9 (pleion agap\u0113sei, "will love more") — the comparative \u03c0\u03bb\u03b5\u1fd6\u03bf\u03bd is deliberate: not merely that the greater debtor loves, but that they love in proportion to the forgiveness received.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
  ParableGroup(
    heading: 'Counting the Cost',
    parables: [
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Wise and Foolish Builders',
        reference: 'Matthew 7:24\u201327',
        theme: 'Foundation',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Counting the Cost/FoolishBuilder.webp',
        icon: Icons.foundation_rounded,
        summary: 'Two builders, one storm. A life built on Jesus\u2019s words stands; anything else does not.',
        verse: '"Everyone therefore who hears these words of mine, and does them, I will liken him to a wise man, who built his house on a rock. The rain came down, the floods came, and the winds blew, and beat on that house; and it didn\'t fall, for it was founded on the rock. Everyone who hears these words of mine, and doesn\'t do them will be like a foolish man, who built his house on the sand."',
        statementInBrief: 'Two houses look the same until the storm comes. The only difference is foundation: rock (hearing and doing Jesus\' words) versus sand (hearing but not doing). The parable closes the Sermon on the Mount: the issue was never information but obedience.',
        centralPointTitle: 'The storm reveals what your life is built on — not what you believe but what you do',
        centralPoint: 'Both builders heard the same words. The difference is not information received but response enacted. Life\'s storms do not create weakness — they reveal it. The foundation of hearing and doing Jesus\' words is the only one that withstands reality\'s full weight.',
        pdfQuestion: 'What is your life actually built on — and how do you know until the storm comes?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Identify one teaching of Jesus in the Sermon on the Mount (Matt 5–7) that you hear but have not yet acted on. Begin this week.',
          'Reflect on a storm you have been through: what did it reveal about what your life was built on?',
          'Read Psalm 127:1 alongside this parable: "Unless the Lord builds the house, those who build it labour in vain."',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'This parable is the conclusion of the Sermon on the Mount — Jesus\' grand ethical discourse. It closes not with a doctrine but with a demand: hearing is not enough. The whole discourse has been preparing this conclusion: the Kingdom life requires doing, not just knowing.',
        historicalContext: 'Palestinian houses were often built in riverbeds which were dry most of the year. A builder who chose the sandy riverbed was building with ease in view, not durability. A house on rock required more effort and preparation but withstood the seasonal flash floods that could fill the wadi in hours.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'France reads this as the Sermon\'s "bottom line": the entire discourse is the words one must hear and do. The parable thus functions as a summary application. The identical storm tests both houses — the parable does not offer shelter from storms, but adequacy for them.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u1f00\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c9\u03bd... \u03ba\u03b1\u1f76 \u03c0\u03bf\u03b9\u1ff6\u03bd ("hearing and doing") — both present participles, indicating ongoing, habitual activity. The wise builder is not someone who once obeyed but someone whose life pattern is hearing-and-doing. \u03c0\u03b5\u03c4\u03c9\u03c3\u03b9\u03c2 (pt\u014dsis, "fall") — the word used of the foolish builder\'s house describes a catastrophic, complete collapse, not a mere wobble.',
      ),
      ParableModel(
        title: 'The Lowest Seat at the Feast',
        reference: 'Luke 14:7\u201311',
        theme: 'Humility',
        imagePath: 'assets/parables/Counting the Cost/The Lowest Seat at the Feast.webp',
        icon: Icons.chair_rounded,
        summary: 'The one who humbles himself will be exalted. Kingdom values invert the world\u2019s social order.',
        verse: 'He spoke a parable to those who were invited, when he noticed how they chose the best seats, and said to them, "When you are invited by anyone to a marriage feast, don\'t sit in the best seat, since perhaps someone more honorable than you might be invited by him, and he who invited both of you would come and tell you, \'Make room for this person.\' Then you would begin, with shame, to take the lowest place. But when you are invited, go and sit in the lowest place, so that when he who invited you comes, he may tell you, \'Friend, move up higher.\' Then you will be honored in the presence of all who sit at the table with you."',
        statementInBrief: 'Jesus observes guests jostling for places of honour at a dinner and addresses them: do not seek the high place — you may be demoted publicly. Seek the low place, and you may be elevated. The Kingdom reverses human systems of self-promotion: whoever exalts himself will be humbled; whoever humbles himself will be exalted.',
        centralPointTitle: 'In the Kingdom, the way up is down — self-exaltation leads to shame, self-humbling to honour',
        centralPoint: 'Jesus is not merely offering social wisdom about avoiding embarrassment. He is describing the structural logic of God\'s Kingdom: honour belongs to the humble, and the self-promoter will be exposed. The concluding axiom (v. 11) is the parable\'s real point.',
        pdfQuestion: 'In what area of life are you currently seeking the best seat — the recognition, the credit, the prominent position?',
        pdfPractices: [
          'Practice actively giving credit to others this week — at work, at home, at church — without claiming it for yourself.',
          'Read Philippians 2:3–4 alongside this parable: "count others more significant than yourselves."',
          'Ask: where am I angling for the best seat in my relationships, career, or ministry? Consciously move to the lower one.',
        ],
        audienceContext: 'Jesus is at a leading Pharisee\'s dinner (Luke 14:1) on the Sabbath. He heals a man with dropsy, addresses the host about inviting the poor (not just reciprocal dinner guests), and then tells this parable about the guests\' behaviour — three distinct challenges in one meal.',
        historicalContext: 'Seating at formal dinners in the ancient world was a matter of social status — proximity to the host was a visible marker of honour. Displacing a guest who had taken a higher seat than was appropriate was a public humiliation. The culture of social climbing Jesus addresses was real and pervasive.',
        scholarlyInterpretation: 'Green notes that Luke frames this as a "parable" (v. 7), elevating it from mere social advice to a Kingdom principle. The concluding axiom in v. 11 links this to the great reversal theme throughout Luke: the proud will be scattered, the humble lifted up (cf. Luke 1:51–52). Jesus is not offering a social strategy but describing the Kingdom\'s inversion of human systems.',
        exegeticalNotes: '\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03b5\u03b9\u03bd\u1f79\u03c9\u03bd \u1f11\u03b1\u03c5\u03c4\u03cc\u03bd (tapein\u014dn heauton, "humbling himself") — the same verb used in Philippians 2:8 of Christ\'s self-humbling unto death. The divine passive \u1f51\u03c8\u03c9\u03b8\u03ae\u03c3\u03b5\u03c4\u03b1\u03b9 (hyps\u014dth\u0113setai, "will be exalted") points to God as the agent of the exaltation — human self-promotion cannot achieve what only God can give.',
      ),
    ],
  ),
];
